  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "Surviving Your First Month Abroad: A Step-by-Step Guide",
  "description": "Learn what to prioritize during your first month abroad, from finding long-term housing to registering with local authorities.",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "Migrating Mammals"
  },
  "mainEntity": {
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What should I do on my first day abroad?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Your immediate priorities are getting cash in the local currency, activating your local SIM card or eSIM, and getting safely to your temporary accommodation."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How long should I book temporary housing for?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "We recommend booking an Airbnb, hostel, or hotel for at least 2 to 4 weeks. This gives you enough time to tour long-term apartments in person to avoid scams."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do I make friends in a new country?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Join local Facebook expat groups, attend language exchange meetups, work from coworking spaces, or join a local sports club."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
};

export const meta = {
  title: "First Month Abroad: A Step-by-Step Guide",
  description: "Learn what to prioritize during your first month abroad, from finding long-term housing to registering with local authorities.",
  category: "guide",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};
---
<SiteLayout site="migratingmammals" title="First Month Abroad: A Step-by-Step Guide" description="Learn what to prioritize during your first month abroad, from finding long-term housing to registering with local authorities." canonical="https://migratingmammals.com/first-month-abroad-guide" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>First Month Abroad</h1>
      <p>Housing, registration, and settling in.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <p>You've arrived! After months of planning, packing, and paperwork, you are finally in your new home. However, the work isn't over. Your first month is critical for establishing your legal and logistical foundation. Here is exactly what you need to prioritize.</p>

      <h2>Week 1: Immediate Logistics</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Get Connected:</strong> As outlined in our <a href="/guide-phone-plan-abroad">Phone Plans Guide</a>, buy a local SIM card immediately so you have data and a local number.</li>
          <li><strong>Get Cash:</strong> Withdraw a small amount of local currency using a no-fee debit card for cash-only establishments.</li>
          <li><strong>Rest and Recover:</strong> Give yourself a few days to unpack at your temporary housing and recover from jet lag. Do not rush into signing contracts on day one.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Week 2: Legal and Financial Setup</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Register Your Address:</strong> In many countries (especially in Europe), you must register your temporary or permanent address with the local city hall within 8 to 14 days of arrival.</li>
          <li><strong>Open a Local Bank Account:</strong> Once you have your registration certificate, visit a local bank to open a basic checking account. Learn more in our <a href="/guide-international-banking">Banking Guide</a>.</li>
          <li><strong>Get Your Tax ID:</strong> Apply for your local tax identification number if it was not issued with your visa.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Week 3: Finding Long-Term Housing</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>Never sign a long-term lease sight unseen from abroad. Scams are incredibly common.</p>
        <p>Spend your third week touring apartments in person. Check the water pressure, look for signs of mold, and test the commute to your workplace or favorite coworking space. Once you find a place, you will likely need to pay a security deposit of 1 to 3 months' rent via a bank transfer.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Week 4: Community and Routine</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>With your housing and legal affairs sorted, you can focus on building your new life.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Set Up Utilities:</strong> Contact local electricity, water, and internet providers to switch the bills into your name.</li>
          <li><strong>Find Your Spots:</strong> Locate your nearest grocery store, pharmacy, and gym.</li>
          <li><strong>Make Friends:</strong> Join local expat Facebook groups, language exchange meetups (like InterNations or Meetup.com), or start working from a local coworking space to meet people.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Cross-Links and Related Information</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>This guide represents Phase 5 of the ultimate <a href="/moving-abroad-checklist">Moving Abroad Checklist</a>. Be sure to review the entire checklist to ensure you didn't miss any critical pre-departure steps.</p>
        <p>If your shipped boxes haven't arrived yet, check your tracking info or review our <a href="/guide-shipping-belongings">Shipping Belongings Guide</a> for estimated timelines.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>What should I do on my first day abroad?</h3>
        <p>Your immediate priorities are getting cash in the local currency, activating your local SIM card or eSIM, and getting safely to your temporary accommodation.</p>

        <h3>How long should I book temporary housing for?</h3>
        <p>We recommend booking an Airbnb, hostel, or hotel for at least 2 to 4 weeks. This gives you enough time to tour long-term apartments in person to avoid scams.</p>

        <h3>How do I make friends in a new country?</h3>
        <p>Join local Facebook expat groups, attend language exchange meetups, work from coworking spaces, or join a local sports club.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <script is:inline>
    console.log("First month abroad guide loaded.");
  </script>
